{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_goyle_ver01/data/sn82007637/00516993832/1958052301/0276.xml":{"full_text":"THE\nUNION JOURNAL\u2019S\nEditorial Page\nFriday, May, 23, 1958\nGOP Says \u2018No\u2019\nTo Jobless In Ohio\nTHE READING of roll call votes may be\ndull reading but not if you\u2019re out of\nwork and want to find out who your\nfriends may be. For example, let\u2019s look at\nthe recent roll call vote in the U.S. House\nof Representatives on unemployment com\npensation.\nUp for a vote was a bill to extend un\nemployment compensation 16 weeks and\nprovide benefits for the jobless not pro\ntected by state compensation laws.\nThe House voted 223-165 to reject the\nbill in favor of a weaker bill that called\nfor the extension of benefits by only 13\nweeks and excluded the unemployed not\ncovered by state programs.\nThe Ohio delegation in the House is\nmade up of 17 Republicans and six Demo\ncrats. The 17 Republicans either voted\nagainst or were paired against the bill\nwhile the six Democrats lined up on the\nside of the liberal bill.\nAs Rep. John W. McCormack of Mas\nsachusetts remarked to a reporter after\nthe vote:\nIf I\nwere\nrunning\nin\na\nclose\ndistrict, I\u2019d love to have this as an issue.\u201d\nThat is a roll call vote to keep in mind\nwhen we go to the polls and cast our votes\nin November.\nLet\u2019s Pass This Bill\nAMIDST ALL the hue and cry on the\nneed for labor legislation to curb im\nproper practices there goes practically un\nnoticed a bill supported by the AFL-CIO,\nthe Administration and members of both\nparties for across-the-board disclosure of\nthe administration of all welfare funds.\nThe Douglas-Kennedy-Ives bill cleared\nthe Senate on a unanimous vote. It pres\nently rests before the House Labor Com\nmittee awaiting action.\nThis bill deals effectively with one of\nthe major areas of improper practices in\nlabor-management relations. Its passage\nby the House and approval by the White\nHouse deserves top priority in any con\ngressional program on labor legislation.\nThe House committee should clear it\npromptly for a vote by the full chamber.\nEditorial Comment\nHE Ohio Chamber of Commerce, nor\nmally a staunch opponent of \u2018govern\nT\nment regulation of business,\u2019 is now spon\nsoring a proposal to put a constitutional\namendment prohibiting the \u2018union shop\u2019\non the Ohio ballot in November. It would\nseem that the Chamber of Commerce has\ndecided that government regulation is a\nfine thing when it benefits the big manu\nfacturer, and is \u2018creeping socialism' only\nwhen it benefits the working man or the\ncommon citizen.\"\n\u201cIf labor unions were so powerful that\nmanagement needed this help in order to\ndeal on even terms with them, the legis\nlation might be needed. No one, observing\nthe working man in queues at the em\nployment offices and the representatives\nof management, on the other hand, bask\ning in the sun in Florida, will argue ser\niously that such help is needed.\u201d (Yellow\nSprings, O., News)\nDon\u2019t Wait for November\nw\nHILE THE NATION\u2019S attention is\nriveted on the recession, atomic dis\narmament and eruptions of violence in\ncritical areas of the globe, the men who\nwill ultimately shape America\u2019s policies\non these and other questions are being se\nlected in state primary elections\nLabor has a large stake in the out\ncome of these primary elections, for they\ndetermine whether or not in November\na candidate who is enlightened and in\nformed on foreign policy, who supports\nlabor's anti-recession program, the fight\non the open shoppers and the goal of se\ncuring appropriate labor legislation to\ncurb improper practices, will be on the\nballot.\nIn the seven primaries held to date\nand the score or so scheduled for the next\n60 days, the make-up of the 86th Con\ngress may be determined beyond repair\nin November.\nIt\u2019s time to couple the fight on unem\nployment with political action, the fight\nfor a sound foreign policy with an inten\nORGANIZE TOLEDO 100%\nOfficial Publication of Organized Labor\nIn Northwestern Ohio\nGrand\nAward\nWinner\nEntered at Toledo, Ohio, Post Office as second\nclass matter under the act of Aug. 24, 1912\nPublished Every Friday\nPublishing Office, 425 Winthrop Street\nToledo, Ohio\nPar Information Phone CH. 1-9129\nWalter Murphy\nWilliam Borden\nDerele Collins\nMelvin Zimkowski,\nEditor\nSports Editor\nCirculation Manager\nEdmond A. Pawlickf Journal Cameramen\nWalter Murphy, Charles Ballard,\nOtte Beebe (Local 248) Board of Trustees\nDave Huber. Director of Advertising\nTelephone Advertising Department\nCH. 4-4499 and CH. 6-1141\nMember Trade Union Advertising, N\u00ab X.\nsive registration drive, the fight against\nlegislation designed to cripple unions with\na \"know-the-issues\" campaign. And to\nmake all these effective a determined ef\nfort is needed to collect contributions for\nCOPE.\nNovember may be too late. Let\u2019s get\ngoing now!\nA\nAs Vandercook\nSees it...\nJ\nIke Resists Own Advice\nAS THE RECESSION, more slowly per\nhaps, but just as surely, worsens, we\nare assured the way to win back pros\nperity is to buy practically anything.\nPres. Eisenhower has given us that ad\nvice. His exhortation to buy has been\nechoed by advertising men who, with\nsome reason, have assured their clients\nthat Americans can still be persuaded to\nbuy the things they want and need if\nthey have sufficient urging; and maybe,\nof course, some money.\nBy buying, by spending, and by reduc\ning our standards of living no more than 1\nwe absolutely must, we are sternly in\nformed by many of our chosen leaders, in\nsuch a way sometimes as to make the\nwhole recession seem to be our fault, we\ncan show our confidence in the future of\nAmerica. Then, the long-awaited \u201cup\nturn\u201d will begin.\nThat, of course, is perfectly good ad\nvice. It is true that one of the greatest\ndangers of a slippage in our economy is\nthat tens of millions of us, who actually\nneed not be, may be affected by recession\npsychology and will begin to practice un\nnecessary economies.\nSo sound, indeed, is that advice, that\nit is becoming more and more puzzling\nwhy it is being resisted so energetically\nby Mr. Eisenhower and by the Republi\ncan Administration, for this is the para\ndox. While you and I are being told to\nloosen up and help spend America back to\nfull employment, the White House and\nmost of the President\u2019s party in Congress\nflatly refuse to practice their own preach\ning.\nWe\u2019re informed that there\u2019s still a lot\nof money around. That\u2019s correct. The\ncurrent savings of the American people,\naccording to an estimate made by the Se\ncurities and Exchange Commission, are\nnow reckoned at about $141 billion. Credit\nis easier. Interest rates are down.\nBut all that, it might be said, applies\nequally to that immense, collective, and\nhugely influential entity, the- United\nStates of America itself. What, on reflec\ntion, could be more encouraging than for\nthe government of the U.S. to show faith\nin the future of the United States by em\nbarking on an inspiring spending project\nof its own? Citizens aren\u2019t being asked\nto waste their money.\nBut then, assuredly, neither are the\nadvocates of massive public works pro\ngrams asking the United States to waste\nits limitless credit, or our money. We\nneed to build a colossal number of new\nschool-rooms. Harbors, sources of water\npower, airports clamor to be developed.\nGreat rivers offer a choice between\nplenty and destruction.\nWhat better time could there be to\nembark on the projects than right now?\nThe President and his colleagues com\nplain that major public works under\ntakings do not produce massive, immedi\nate employment, but they\u2019re a start\ntoward it.\nThrough The Years\nWith The Toledo Union Journal\nFIFTEEN TEARS AGO\nMAT 28, 1943: Hundreds of Toledo work\ners under the leadership of Local 12 UAW-CIO.\nstaged a demonstration Monday afternoon\nand evening before the district Office of Price\nAdministration in protest against OPA meth\nods of freezing wages and continued inflation\nof price* Member* of Auto-Lite Unit of\nLocal 12, UAW-CIO, voted to return to work\nafter a 2-day work stoppage when George\nAddis. secretary-treasurer of the International'\nUnion, UAW-CIO told them they were not\ngaining anything by remaining away from\nwork because the entire matter of wage in\ncrease* was up to the War Labor Board for a\nruling.\nTEN TEARS AGO\nMAT 28, 1948: Over 300 delegates, repre\nsenting 60,000 Region 2-B UAW-CIO member*\nattended the regional conference May 22 at\nMarion, Ohio, and adopted 11 resolutions in\ncluding higher wages for school teachers, sup\nport of the Chrysler strike and rollback of\nprices. There 1* little to cheer about as a\ngovernment report show* that the price index\nha* hit an all-time high.\nFIVE TEARS AGO\nMAT 29, 1933: The CIO and AFL are not\nletting any grass grow under in the event of\nmass unemployment They have named a com\nmittee to map plans to attract new industry\nto Toledo. President Eisenhower, true to\nform named another banker, Saumel C.\nWaugh of Lincoln, Neb., to assistant secre\ntary of state for economic affairs. The ex\nport import trade to Toledo in 1952 amounted\nto a total of $134,200,000, an all-time record,\nand this without real port facilities as the St.\nLawrence Seaway would give for proper ship\ntraffic.\nX\nSpringtime in\nWashington, 1958\n2\nHOUSE\nOF LABOR\nit\nL\nP\n0\nte\np.2\n05\n\u25a0MWHfflim\nIWIIMRO\nThink It Over\nDishonest Hucksters\nBy PETE ZVARA\niiiiiiriHBiifliuiiiiniiWM\nlifldle\nT\nIHE LEADERS of the Ohio Chamber of\nCommerce, along with all others who are\nengaged in directing and financing the so\ncalled Ohio right-to-work law campaign, are\npure and simple dishonest hucksters.\nThey are dishonest be\ncause they know that their\nright-to-work law has noth\ning whatever to do with the\nright of a worker to a job.\nTherein lies their duplicity,\ntheir reprehensible double\nstandard steeped in their\nown lies and misinformation.\nHow tragically these dis\nhonest hucksters confuse and\ndeliberately deceive sincere\nand honest people was shock\ningly illustrated in the re\nPete Zvara\ncent primary election voting. I son told that in\na single voting booth in Akron a communi\nty, like Toledo and others, heavily hit by un\nemployment nineteen women voters asked\nfor the \u201cright-to-work law ballot so that they\ncould vote for it \u201cbecause we want our hus\nbands to get jobs.\u201d\nThere were similar incidents in other parts\nof the State.\nAnd why not? Is there a wife who would\nnot vote for a \u201cright-to-work law\u201d if by so do\ning her jobless husband would be put back to\nwork?\nAnd is there an honest worker within our\nranks not to mention those who are already\njobless who would oppose a law that would\nassure his right to a job?\nWell, this is exactly what these dishonest\nhucksters are predicating their entire cam\npaign on. They KNOW they have to deceive,\nmisinform and in general resort to the shadiest\ntricks of huckstering to get people to support\nthem.\nIf ever there was a determined attempt to\nput Hitler's \u201cBig Lie\u201d tactic across the Ameri\ncan people, this is it.\nThis is why decent employers in Ohio who\ndesire to maintain truthful and stable relations\nwith their employees condemn these shady\ntricks. Unfortunately these employers, perhaps\nbecause they fear intimidation. are hesitant to\nspeak out against this campaign of deceit and\nlies as they should, and as they will, we\nhope.\nFurther, this is why such dominant sections\nof all denominations of our clergy includ\ning the Catholic Bishops of Ohio condemn\nthe shabby tricks of these dishonest hucksters.\n\nAS ALL HONEST and intelligent people\nknow, the real purpose of the proposed \u201cright\nto-work law\u201d is to weaken, and if at all pos\nsible destroy, labor unions everywhere.\nThis is not difficult to understand. After\nall, if an employer is able to weaken or to de- 4\nstroy the union he deals with, he can immedi\nately \u201cwrite his own ticket\u201d as the saying\ngoes. And they would, but fast. This would\nmean lower wages and benefits of every type\nour people now enjoy it would mean the\ndestruction of Job security and a rapid de\n\u2019velopment of speed-up in all planta.\nThis situation would bring about more\nprofits for the bosses and less wages, less ben\nefits. less protection for the workers.\nThis is the true aim of the proposed \u201cright\nto-work law\u201d Ohio's dishonest hucksters are\npushing with such frenzy, such determination\nand such large bankrolls\nLetters To The Editor\nGives Thanks\nTO THE EDITOR:\nMay I take this opportunity\nto thank each and every one\nof all the brothers and sisters\npersonally for your most wel\ncomed and appreciated help\ning hand you so graciously ex\ntended to me in my recent bid\nfor State Representative from\nLucas County.\nAlthough my good friend,\nFrancis Reno, practically as\nsured me I could expect to\nfinish in 4th or Sth place if\nonly I were able to garner at\nleast 8,000 votes, as it turned\nout I was fortunate enough to\nget 11,144 votes to finish out\n8th in a large field of 14\naspirants, and another very\nclose friend of mine made the\nclassic remark \u201cIf your name\nwould have been \u201cCarey\u201d in\nstead of \"Curly\" you might\nhave made 4th or Sth spot\nfor sure.\nStrange as it may sound.\nnone of the above has left me\nwith a defeatist attitude, but\nrather has taught me to be\nmore appreciative of the fact\nthat LABOR was almost sole\nly responsible for the large\nnumber of votes I received.\nmore than most any candi\ndate might have expected to\nreceive the very first time he\nran for any Office. Likewise\nI am sure that it made the\nvast majority of candidates\nand voters alike set up and\ntake notice, that LABOR can\nelect any candidate or pass\nany issue \"It\u201d feels worthy to\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0MHanHMMMIIHW\nWorker* and their families would indeed\nbe fools to vote for this kind of a program.\nAnd decent people in all walks of life, once\nthey really understand the issues, must reject\nwith repugnance this so-called \u201cright-to-work\u201d\nprogram which is so manifestly based in de\nceit and lies.\n\n\n\nTHERE MAY be honest people, of course, who\nreally believe that the proposed \u201cright-to\nwork\u201d law is Just that. Like the women voters\nin Akron, they feel sure that by voting into\nlaw such a proposal they are in fact voting for\nthe right to a job for themselves and their\nloved ones.\nWell, the best way to answer that assump\ntion is to point to other states that have \u201cright\nto-work\u201d laws such as the one being proposed\nin Ohio.\nAnd for this we don\u2019t have to go very far.\nIn neighboring Indiana they have such a\nlaw. I believe it was adopted a little over a\nyear ago, following the same type of campaign\nas the one we are witnessing in Ohio. So, what\nare the results? Do workers in Indiana have a\nright to a job? Are they working more so than\nin Ohio? Obviously not. The steel mills of\nGary, the industrial plants of South Bend,\nIndianapolis and other Indiana communities\nare just as slow in their operations as are the\nplanta in other states.\nWhat about the sixteen other states that\nhave similar right-to-work laws, such as Vir\nginia and Arkansas just to mention two? Do\nthe workers in these states have the right to a\njob? Are they working? Or are they faced\nwith joblessness just as much as workers in\nthose states that do not have these misnamed\nmonstrosities called \u201cright-to-work laws?\u201d\nObviously unemployment is just as pre\nvalent in these \"right-to-work law\u201d states as\nanywhere else.\nBut there is something else in these states\nsomething very significant. Lower wages\nin everyone of them, with the sole exception of\nNevada. There, of course, the explanation for\nthis unusual circumstance can be found in two\npeculiar characteristics of this peculiar state:\n(1) in the wide open and legal gambling in*\ndustry, and (2) in the fact that what little in*\ndustry this sparsely settled state has is to be\nfound in manufacturing and mining, both in*\ndustries in the relatively high wage paying\nareas.\nBut everywhere else, every other state\nwhere the \u201cright-to-work\u201d law has been\nadopted, we find lower wages some of them\nin tile Deep South, really miserably low\nand weak unions.\nTo establish similar conditions in Ohio is\nthe true aim of the \u201cright-to-work\u201d law advo\ncates, no matter what they say or how they\ntry by employing the worst examples of dis\nhonest huckstering to disguise their true\naims.\nTo fall for this line, therefore, is to be\ncome dupes of people whose sole aim is selfish\ngreed of the most reprehensible kind.\nI have great confidence that there are\nenough people in Ohio who refuse to be and\nwill not become dupes for anyone, including\nthe advocates and messengers of this classic\ncampaign of lies and deceit. Rather, the good\npeople of Ohio will treat these so-called \u201cright\nto-work law\u201d advocates with contempt\u2014the\nusual treatment accorded to and deserved by\nevery dishonest huckster no matter where they\noperate or whet they try to dupe the people\nwith.\nreceive LABOR\u2019S support, and\ndefeat any issue or Candidate\n\u201cIt\u201d deems unworthy of LA\nBOR\u2019S support.\nIn closing, again I wish to\nthank each and every one of\nyou from the bottom of my\nheart, for your most heart\n.warming efforts and deeds\nduring the May 6, 1958 Pri\nmary Election, and may I\nsuggest you just work just a\n\u201cMite\u201d harder to defeat the\nso called \u201cFreedom of Choice\u201d\nLaw that will confront us\nwith it\u2019s appearance on the\nNovember Election Ballot.\nMay God Bless and bring\ngood luck and good strong\nhealth to LABOR and its\nCAUSE\nTHOMAS P CURLEY\nLocal 9 Glass Workers\na\n3\nYour Union\n\n\n\n\n4\n\u201cA\nAnd Mine h\n\nIs\nBy RICHARD T. GOSSER\nVice President. UAW\nI THOUGHT I'd take this occasion to say a few words to\nthe readers of the Toledo Union Journal because I\nthink it important this be said, so we might all take stock\nof ourselves. We have to recognize the fact that the U. S.\nChamber of Commerce, the National Association of Manu\nfacturers are really sending out propaganda over the radio and\nTV and in the public press And what are they saying? They\u2019d\nhave you believe it was the working man's fault he is unem\nployed today rather than the lack of proper management on the\npart of the government and the employers. They especially say\nnothing about the large corporate interests that have been and\nstill are making more profit on the invested dollar than they\nshould\nAnd now the latest idea, and this should really be made\ninto a comic strip, is everyone is struggling to develop ways of\ncreating job opportunities. The most publicized way at the mo\nment is they have started a \u201cbuy\u201d slogan all over America. I\ndon\u2019t know how anyone can buy if you don't have a job, and\neven those who have a job don\u2019t know when they might get\nlaid off.\nThe fact is we are in a dilemma and the blame for it should\nbe put where it rightfully belongs. And that is on the shoulders\nof the Administration and the Congress and Senate of the\nUnited States. Why don\u2019t they quit talking like Hoover. He used\nto say \"Prosperity is around the corner.\u201d Eisenhower is always\nsaying today \"Business is picking up the trend is better.\u201d\nWe all know this is malarky.\n\nWHAT SHOULD THE ADMINISTRATION BE DOING?\nIt could create a Public Works Program. There are plenty of\nthings that could be done throughout the country such as de\nveloping playgrounds, building schools, hospitals, recreational\ncenters, proper housing, modern highways and byways.\nSuch a Public Works Program would put every unemploy\ned sister and brother back to work at a salary at a proper rate\nso they could live with dignity. Then slowly as these people\ncould buy, they would start feeding money back into the econ\nomy of our nation and people would be absorbed into the fac\ntories and mills. This is the way this recession we have event\nually will be licked.\nC\n\nIt\u2019s all right for anyone who is still working to say some\nthing otherwise than this, but if you were a young, healthy fel\nlow raising a family, you would want a job of your own at dec\nent wages so you might hold your head high and support your\nfamily in dignity. I say to all of you still working, think of your\nsisters and brothers who are unemployed and think of how you\nwould feel in their position.\nAnd there's something else that could be done. What would\nbe wrong with retirement at the age 60? That would let a fel\nlow get started in his retirement before he was too old to enjoy\nit. And it would create a lot of job opportunities because there\nare seven million people between the ages of 60 and 65 and\nthere are only 5% million unemployed. Now all the people that\nsay this would create a tax too high to pay ught to remember\nthat this tax will be created in some form anyway. And what is\nmore decent than to give a person who has spent thirty or forty\nyears laboring a chance to sit down and enjoy the latter part\nof his life. He'd also be making room for his sons and daughters\nto go to work.\nc\nWE LIVE IN a society that up until now has failed to ad\njust its economy properly so that people can buy things they\nproduce. Our country has everything, we only lack intelligent\npeople to lead it properly so that all can share in the fruits of\ntheir labor and enjoy life as it should be.\nI am going to close this column this week by giving these\nlittle ideas to the people in Washington so they can think about\nthem. And I hope some of you will take the time to write to\nyour Congressman and Senators asking them to act on them.\nDon\u2019t be misled by the propaganda of those who would say\nlabor is responsible for where we are today. Remember you are\na part of labor and you are the one being hurt and you have\nhad nothing whatsoever to do with creating this situation. But\nyou can do something about getting the country out of thia\nrecession.\nLet's work together.\nLet\u2019s write our Congressmen and our Senators a letter.\nLet\u2019s demand two things\u2014retirement at age 60 and a Pub\nlic Works Program now.\nThat way we all can buy the things we need now and we\nwill have some insurance that people will be able to buy things\nthey need in the years to come.\n4\nBulletin Board\nMeetings scheduled for week of May 24 thru May 30th\nSaturday, May 24\nGOODFELLOWS PARTY 8 :00 P.M. Parlor A\nACKLIN STAMPING 10:00 A.M. Parlor H\nSunday, May 25\nNATIONAL SUPPLY 10:00 A.M. Parlor,A\nMonday, May 26\nT.I.U.C. 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nCITY MACHINE 10:00 A.M. Parlor B\nTuesday, May 27\nCHAIRMEN\u2019S MEETING 10:00 A.M. Parlor A\nTOLEDO SCALE 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nCITY MACHINE 7:30 P.M. Parlor B\nAMERICAN BRAKE 7:30 P.M. Parlor C\nCOLUMBIA BURNER 7:30 P.M. Parlor H\nWednesday, May 28\nLUCAS COUNTY UNEMPLOYMENT\nCOUNCIL 8:00 P.M. Parlor A\nFORMED STEEL 8:00 P.M. Parlor B\nSULLIVAN STEEL 7:00 P.M. Parlor C\nDUPONT 8:00 P.M. Parlor H\nThursday; May 29\nCHAMPION ELEC. COM. 8:30 A.M. Parlor B\nSAVE ELECTRIC 8:00 P.M. Parlor C\nCAMP COUNSELLORS 7:00 P.M. Parlor H\nFriday, May 38\nNONE SCHEDULED HOLIDAY\no\nC\nOTHER LOCAL UNION MEETINGS\nNEWSPAPER PRESSMEN\n1st Tuesday 6 P.M. Carpenters* Hall\nPHOTO ENGRAVERS\n2nd Monday 5:30 P.M. 61212 Huron St.\nBOOKBINDERS\n2nd Thursday 5 P.M. 912 Adams St\nRETAIL CLERKS\n1st Wednesday 8 P.M. 215% Summit St.\nMAILERS\n3rd Monday 6 P.M. 612% Huron St.\nALLIED PRINTING TRADES COUNCIL\n1st Friday 612 12 Huron St\nPRINTING PRESSMEN ASSISTANTS NO. 55\n4th Friday 612% Huron St\nCOMMUNICATION WORKERS, LOCAL 4319\n2nd Thursday 8:30 P.M. 706% Monroe St\nr\nr","height":"26816","width":"19536"}}
